NarNarrative: This antler of a red deer is probably only a few hundred years old and not a true fossil. However, red deer antlers are sometimes found in peat beds that formed about 7500 years ago as the climate warmed up after the last glaciation. They migrated into the glaciated areas as the vegetation grew. The horns that are cast off annually are often the only remains that are found of the deer.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil reptile (ichthyosaur), Ichthyosaurus campylodon, collected from the Greensand (?) of Early Cretaceous, Aptian - Albian age.
NarNarrative: This jaw fragment is from a marine reptile known as an Ichthyosaur which, grew up to 3m long and looked like a dolphin with a long snout. Its cone-shaped teeth fit closely together and have distinctive vertical grooves. Ichthyosaurs were predators and scavengers that fed mainly on fish, ammonites and belemnites. They were unusual reptiles because they gave birth to live young (most reptiles lay eggs on land). This may have been an adaptation to their marine habitat.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Platysomus striatus, collected from the Marl Slate of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ1 age from Thrislington Quarry, Ferryhill, Co Durham (NE England). Collected by S.G. McLean, 2001.
NarNarrative: Platysomus striatus was a deep-bodied fish that lived in the Zechstein Sea 250 million years ago. It was probably a slow swimmer, and may have lived among seaweed and small reefs near the shore. Platysomus had blunt cone-shaped teeth, ideal for crushing and eating shellfish. The lower part of the fish is missing from this fossil, but it is very rare to find complete fossils of this fish.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil mammal (Mammoth), Mammuthus primigenius, collected from unspecified rocks of Quaternary age. Tooth and partial jaw.
NarNarrative: Woolly mammoths became extinct about 10 000 years ago and are symbolic of the Ice Ages in the Quaternary period. They are well known from Stone Age (Palaeolithic) cave paintings and the discovery of complete bodies in frozen ground in Siberia. They probably used their long tusks to scrape away snow and ice from the plants they fed on. Mammoth are often regarded as being extremely large but the biggest were about the same size as a fully grown African bull elephant. The distinctive ridges on the teeth were used to grind down the tough grasses that they fed on.
ComName_tab: Mammoth, Mammuthus primigenius, Mammuthus primigenius

NarNarrative: Coccosteus was a fish that lived in Lake Orcadie, a fresh water lake that covered a large area of Scotland 380 million years ago during the Devonian period. Its head and upper body were covered with protective bony plates while the rest of its body was scaly. This fish was a hunter, the bony plates in its mouth had sharp edges, a bit like steak knives, which it used like shears to bite off bits of its prey.

Ichthyosaurs were predators and scavengers that fed mainly on fish, ammonites and belemnites.

NarNarrative: This is one bone (vertebra), from the back of a plesiosaur, a large marine reptile that lived at the same time as the dinosaurs. Plesiosaurs were not dinosaurs. They looked a bit like some modern drawings of the Loch Ness monster, with a long neck, small head, and four flippers. They became extinct 65 million years ago.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil reptile (crocodile), collected from the Lower Lias, Jet Rock Formation of Early Jurassic age from Port Mulgrave, North Yorkshire (NE England), UK. Vertebrae.
NarNarrative: This is a single bone (vertebra) from the spine (backbone), of a crocodile that lived 180 million years ago during the Jurassic period. This vertebra is longer than it is wide. The shape and size of the individual vertebrae vary, depending on which part of the backbone they are from, and the age and size of the crocodile. When dinosaurs became extinct 65 million years ago, crocodiles survived. Their appearance has changed little since then.

NarNarrative: Acrolepis was a large, predatory fish, and probably hunted alone, a bit like the modern pike. These large jaws are obviously from a very big fish. Acrolepis would have used its sharp, pointed teeth to help it hold on to the scaly bodies of smaller fish (including the more common Palaeoniscum which lived at the same time as Acrolepis).

NarNarrative: Palaeospondylus gunni is a small fish, which usually measures less than 5cm long. The skull and spine are well-preserved. The fossil is black because these parts have been replaced by carbon. Some experts believe that Palaeospondylus is the juvenile (young) form of a lung fish, but no one knows for sure.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil mammal, an Irish Elk jaw bone with teeth, Megaloceros giganteus, collected from unspecified rocks of Quaternary, Middle to Late Pleistocene age.
NarNarrative: The Irish Elk became extinct about 10,000 years ago. It is now known to be the largest species of deer ever, standing 2 metres high at the shoulder with an antler span up to 4 metres. It lived throughout Europe, northern Asia and northern Africa as well as Ireland. The 'elk' is importance in scientific discovery, because it was one of the first animals to be described as an extinct species by the French Scientist Georges Cuvier in 1812. A large pair of antlers is displayed in the Hancock Museum high up on the stair wall next to the caf?.
ComName_tab: Irish Elk, megaloceros & giganteus (blumenbach), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Mammalia
LocalSum: no locality data

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil reptile, Iguanodon sp., collected from the Tardefurcata Zone = Fissicostatus Zone, Lower Greensand Group, Phosphate Beds (?) of Late (?) Cretaceous, Early Aptian - Albian age from Potton, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire (SE England). Two vertebrae with grove for neural cord.
NarNarrative: These vertebrae were part of the backbone of the large dinosaur Iguanodon. Iguanodon (meaning "iguana tooth") was so named because its teeth look like large versions of the modern iguana. You can see where the spinal chord fitted into the groove on the vertebra. The vertebra was collected from the famous fossil locality at Potton in Bedfordshire. Iguanodon was the second dinosaur ever to be named.
ComName_tab: Dinosaur, Iguanodon
LocalSum: UK, England, Cambridgeshire (SE England), Cambridge, Potton

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Pygopterus sp., collected from the Marl Slate of Late Permian, Zechstein, EZ1 age from Thrislington Quarry, Mainsforth, Co Durham (NE England). Collected by George Fenwick. Mandibles with teeth.
NarNarrative: This fossil is of a jaw bone with teeth, from the a fish called Pygopterus. This fish was quite large, and hunted smaller fish like Palaeoniscum that lived in shoals, a bit like the modern herring. We know that Pygopterus ate Palaeoniscum, because there are fossils of Pygopterus with the remains of Palaeoniscum in the stomach.
ComName_tab: pygopterus & sp., Actinopterygii & Palaeonisciformes (After Romer)
LocalSum: UK, England, Co. Durham (NE England), Ferryhill, Thrislington Gap

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil trace fossil (foot print), Chirotherium sp., collected from unspecified rocks of Middle Triassic, Anisian age from (?), Cheshire (Midland England).
NarNarrative: When William Buckland (an important 19th Century geologist) examined footprint fossils like these ones, he thought that they had probably been made by reptiles that walked on four legs. The fossil was named Chirotherium (which means hand-beast) because they look like hand prints. To test his theory, he made a crocodile walk over pastry, and then took impressions of the track. This showed that the footprints were not made by a crocodile. He carried out the same experiment with tortoises, and decided that the tracks had probably been made by a similar creature. It was not until the 1960s that the fossil animal was identified. It was a reptile that measured about 2.5 metres in length, and had a slim body and a long tail. It was named Ticinosuchus ferox.
ComName_tab: Chirotherium, Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Reptilia

Collected by James Walter Kirkby. Five oval coprolites up to 60 x 20 mm with original card mount.
NarNarrative: These fish droppings called coprolites are from a primitive bony fish with lobe-shaped fins similar to a Coelacanth. Rhizodus grew to a length of 6 or 7 metres and had two large fang-like teeth up to 22cm in length at the front of its the jaw. It lived in freshwater rivers and lakes and was a predator that fed on smaller fish and amphibians. The coprolites were probably preserved in the fish's intestine and found with the fossil fish.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Bothriolepis obesa Traquair, collected from the Upper Old Red Sandstone of Devonian age from Jedburgh (?), Roxburghshire (Scotland). Block bearing several scattered pLates of dermal armour. A number of figures in Miles, R.S. (1968, Pl.XXIII) were drawn from casts and appear to be mirror images of the original material.
NarNarrative: Bothriolepis obesa was an armoured fish that was alive in the Devonian period but is now extinct. Its head and the front part of its body were covered with protective bony plates. It had a pair of long, jointed, bony 'arms', just behind its head. Bothriolepis would have measured about 22 centimetres long. It belonged to a group of primitive fish known as Placoderms.
ComName_tab: bothriolepis & obesa (traquair), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: UK, Scotland, Borders (Scotland), Jedburgh (?)

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Gyracanthus sp., collected from the Coal Measures Group rocks, Modiolaris Zone, of Late Carboniferous, Westphalian, Langsettian - Duckmantian age from Newsham Colliery, Blyth, Northumberland (NE England). Collected by Thomas Atthey. 'Carpal bone'.
NarNarrative: Spines are all that is found of this fish. They may have provided protection against large predators such as sharks. The triangular spine was probably attached to the side of the fish near the pectoral fin. Little is known about the fish except that it probably belonged to a group known as the Acanthodii a few of which grew up to 2m long. The spines are sometimes found with fragments of another fish such as Gyracanthides, but no definite link between the two can be made.

LocalSum: UK, England, Northumberland (NE England), Blyth, Newsham

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil amphibian, Pholiderpeton attheyi, collected from the Modiolaris Zone, Low Main Seam (shale above), Middle Coal Measures of Late Carboniferous, Westphalian, Duckmantian age from Newsham Colliery, Blyth, Northumberland (NE England). Collected by Thomas Atthey. Pleurocentrum and intercentrum with a length of the shaft of a dorsal rib.
NarNarrative: These bones are from a primitive amphibian that looked like a newt but grew up to two metres long - the size of a crocodile! Pholiderpeton was adapted to life in the water and had a long flat-sided tail for swimming. It had four short limbs that it used to walk on land. It lived in lakes and swamps of the tropical coal forests and fed mainly on fish. The species is named after the nineteenth century Newcastle palaeontologist Thomas Atthey.
GeoRock: Coal Measures Formation (Middle) & Low Main Seam (shale above)

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Dorypterus hoffmanni Germar, collected from the Marl Slate of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ1 age from Middridge, Co Durham (NE England). Collected by Joseph Duff, 1869.
NarNarrative: Dorypterus hoffmanni was a deep-bodied fish that lived in the Zechstein Sea (a warm, tropical sea), 250 million years ago. It was probably a slow swimmer, which sheltered among reefs and seaweed. Fossils of this fish are quite rare. There are only four in the UK and three of them are held at the Hancock Museum. The male fish had a very large dorsal (top) fin, which was lacking in females. This might have been used for display to attract a mate.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Rhizodus hibberti, collected from the Lower Coal Measures of Late Carboniferous, Westphalian, Langsettian age from Scotland. Collected by W.D. Dinning.
NarNarrative: This tooth is from a primitive bony fish that grew to a length of 6 or 7 metres. It belonged to a group of fishes with lobe-shaped fins that also included the coelacanths. Rhizodus had two large fang-like teeth (tusks) at the front of the jaw that grew up to 22cm in length. The strong pointed teeth were ideal for hunting prey of smaller fish and amphibians in the freshwater rivers and lakes where the fish lived.
ComName_tab: rhizodus & hibberti (agassiz), Sarcopterygii & Crossoptergyii (After Romer)
LocalSum: UK, Scotland

NarNarrative: This extinct shark's tooth has a serrated (sawtooth-like) edge that helped cut through the flesh of its prey. The teeth are the only fossil remains of this shark that have been found so little is known about it. Its skeleton would have been made out of soft cartilage. LocalSum: UK, England, Yorkshire (NE England), Pateley Bridge

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Deltoptychius acutus, collected from the Carboniferous Limestone of Early Carboniferous, Dinantian, Visean (?) age from Armagh, Ireland. Collected by Thomas Atthey.
NarNarrative: This tooth is from a fish that belongs to a group known as the Chimaera, which are related to sharks. It grew up to 0.45 metres long and lived on the bottom of a warm, shallow tropical sea. The teeth were the only hard part of the fish's body and all that is usually fossilised, since the skeleton was made of cartilage. A pair of teeth was present in both jaws. They were used to crush the shells and crustaceans that the fish ate.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish , Eomyrus latispinus Agassiz, collected from the 'Fish Beds' of Tertiary, Middle Eocene, Lutetian - Bartonian age from Monte Bolca, Verona, Italy. Collected by N.C. Cookson. Part and counterpart. Name means dawn sea-eel with lateral spines.
NarNarrative: The name of this tropical fish means 'dawn sea-eel with lateral spines'. It was collected from one of Europe's earliest and most famous fossil localities, Monte Bolca near Verona in the Italian Alps. The well-preserved fossils fish found there convinced 16th century naturalists that fossils were actually the remains of living organisms. The fish are preserved in a rock deposited on a seabed where there was no oxygen, which prevented any bacterial decay and stopped other animals feeding on their bodies. This is the reason why so many beautiful fossils are found in this area.
ComName_tab: eomyrus & latispinus (agassiz), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: Europe, Italy, Verona, Monte Bolca

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Pterichthyodes sp., collected from unspecified rocks of Late Devonian age from Scotland. Collected by W.D. Dinning.
NarNarrative: Pterichthyodes was an armoured fish. Its head and part of its body were covered with hard bony plates. Just behind its head, it had a paddle on either side of its body, also covered in bony plates, and attached by a ball and socket joint, a bit like the joint in the human shoulder. This fish lived near the bottom of Lake Orcadie, a large inland lake in Scotland, and found its food in the mud of the lake floor.
ComName_tab: pterychthyoides & sp. (?), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: UK, Scotland

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Asterolepis maxima, collected from unspecified rocks of Middle Devonian age from Nairn, Nairnshire (Scotland). Collected by W. Waters.
NarNarrative: Asterolepis maxima was an armoured fish (its head and part of its body were covered with bony plates). It lived during the Middle to Late Devonian Period. The bony plates that covered the head and upper body of this fish had wart like bumps over their surfaces. This fish probably lived on the sea-floor and foraged in the mud for food.
ComName_tab: asterolepis & maxima (agassiz), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: UK, Scotland, Highland (Scotland), Nairn

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Bothriolepis obesa Traquair, collected from the Upper Old Red Sandstone of Devonian age from Jedburgh, Roxburghshire (Scotland). Collected by Matthewson. Anterio-ventral plate.
NarNarrative: Bothriolepis was a fish that had a covering of bony plates over its head and the upper part of its body. Either side of and just behind its head, it had two bony fin-like structures. This fish swallowed mud to get its food. It probably lived near the bottom of a fresh water lake. It belongs to a group of fish known as Placoderms, which had paired fins and simple jaws. The tail, which was not armoured, had no scales and was thin and eel-like.
ComName_tab: bothriolepis & obesa (traquair), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: UK, Scotland, Borders (Scotland), Jedburgh (?)

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish (tooth), a White Shark, Carcharodon megalodon, collected from unspecified rocks of Tertiary age from Battle Hill, Wallsend, Tyne and Wear (NE England). Collected by D. Mould.
NarNarrative: This extinct shark is named after its rough-edged and very large teeth. Often simply know as Megalodon, this was the largest fish that ever lived on the Earth and was three times bigger than its living relative the Great White Shark. It grew up to 17 metres long and had a mouth about 2 metres in diameter. It ruled the warm Tertiary oceans and fed mainly on young whales that it swallowed whole! This fossil was found in Wallsend but was transported there, possibly in ship's ballast.
ComName_tab: White Shark, Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces & Elasmobranchii
LocalSum: UK, England, Tyne and Wear (NE England), Wallsend, Battle Hill

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish , Ctenacanthus hybodoides Egerton, collected from the Modiolaris Zone, Middle Coal Measures, Low Main Seam - Hutton Seam of Late Carboniferous, Westphalian, Duckmantian age from Murton Colliery (?), Murton, Co Durham (NE England). Collected by W.D. Dinning, 1889.
NarNarrative: This fish was a primitive shark that grew up to 1.5m in length. It takes its name from the patterned 'comb spines' that were attached to the front of the two dorsal (upper) fins and buried deep into the muscles on the back of the fish. The fish had a skeleton made of cartilage and usually only the spines and teeth are found as fossils. Ctenacanthus lived in warm tropical seas and the spines provided protection against larger predators.
GeoRock: Coal Measures Formation (Middle) & Low Main Seam - Hutton Seam

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Pygopterus mandibularis, collected from the Marl Slate of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ1 age.
NarNarrative: Pygopterus mandibularis was a large fish that lived in the warm sea that covered the Sunderland area 250 million years ago. Pygopterus ate smaller fishes, such as the herring-like Palaeoniscum, a fish that probably lived in shoals (groups). We know that Pygopterus hunted smaller fish, because there are fossils of Pygopterus with the remains of smaller fish in its stomach.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Acentrophorus varians Kirkby, collected from the Concretionary Limestone of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ2 age from Fulwell Hill, Sunderland, Tyne and Wear (NE England).
NarNarrative: Acentrophorus varians was a small fish, a bit like a sardine, that lived in the Zechstein Sea (a tropical sea that stretched from north east England to Poland) about 250 million years ago. This fish probably lived close to the shore, hiding amongst sea-weeds and avoiding some of the larger predators which also lived in this sea. Acentrophorous had tiny, sharp, conical (cone-shaped) teeth, which it probably used for eating meat. Since it was so small, it was probably a scavenger. Fossils of these fish used to be quite common when there were many working quarries in the Sunderland area. However, they are now very rarely found.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil reptile, Protorosaurus speneri von Meyer, collected from the Marl Slate of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ1 age from Middridge, Co Durham (NE England). Collected by Joseph Duff, 1866.
NarNarrative: Protorosaurus speneri was a lizard-like-reptile that measured between 50 and 100cm long. It was an ancestor of the dinosaurs. It name means 'early lizard'. This fossil is of part of the backbone of Protorosaurus. The vertebrae (the bones that together form the backbone) show up as a grey band. There are only two fossils known in the UK; this is one of them, the other is on display in Sunderland Museum. Protorosaurus was a disapid reptile, meaning that is had two openings on each side of its skull behind the eye sockets, just like dinosaurs.
ComName_tab: Lizard, protorosaurus & speneri (von meyer), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Reptilia
LocalSum: UK, England, Co. Durham (NE England), Midderidge

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Osteolepis macrolepidotus Agassiz, collected from the Upper Old Red Sandstone of Devonian age from Cairnfield, Aberdeenshire (Scotland). Collected by Watson, J., Junior.
NarNarrative: Osteolepis was a fish that lived in a large fresh water lake called Lake Orcadie, that covered a large area of Scotland during the Devonian period. Osteolepis was a fish which probably formed part of the ancestral line from fishes to amphibians and as such is an ancestor of land-based vertebrates (animals with backbones). In this fossil, you can see the head, part of the body, and a fin of this fish. The piece of rock containing the rest of this fossil has broken away.
ComName_tab: , Sarcopterygii & Crossoptergyii (After Romer)
LocalSum: UK, Scotland, Aberdeenshire, Cairnfield

ColPhysicalDescription: Nearly complete specimen showing head and pectoral fin but lacking the caudal area. Atthey, T. (1875 & 1877a) described his new species Palaeoniscus hancocki from numerous specimens collected from Newsham, Cramlington and Kenton which he did not figure. Traquair, R.H. (1910 , p.148) stated that the type specimens were collected and described by the late Mr.Thomas Atthey, and were in the museum of the Natural History Society, Newcastle. He acknowledged the loan of these specimens for the purposes of his work on Rhandinichthys hancocki, and figured two specimens from Atthey's type material (NEWHM G060.11 and NEWHM G060.12). These could therefore be considered as Syntypes.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish tooth, Ceratodus sp., collected from the Rhaetic Bone Bed (?) of Late Triassic, Early Rhaetic age from Aust Cliff on the south side of the River Severn, Gloucestershire (SW England). Collected by J. Goring.
NarNarrative: Ceratodus was a lungfish, which means that it had lungs, as well as gills, unlike other fish. In this fossil, the tooth of Ceratodus is the very shiny dark object. The tooth is attached to a piece of rock (the dull, pale grey part). Modern lungfish don't have stomachs, so they chew their food and then regurgitate it before finally swallowing it.

LocalSum: UK, England, Avon (SW England), Bristol (nr.), Aust Cliff

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish , Ceratodus gulitielni, collected from unspecified rocks at Hoben Beck, Wurtenburg, Germany. Collected by Thomas Atthey.
NarNarrative: Ceratodus was a lungfish (most fish do not have lungs, and use their gills to breathe), that lived during the Mesozoic era. It was thought to be extinct, but related fish that have lungs that are so well developed that they can leave the water and breathe air have recently been discovered in Australian rivers.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish (tooth), Deltoptychius acutus, collected from the Carboniferous Limestone of Early Carboniferous, Dinantian, Visean (?) age from Armagh, Ireland. Collected by Thomas Atthey.
NarNarrative: This tooth is from a fish that belongs to a group known as the Chimaera, which are related to sharks. It grew up to 0.45 metres long and lived on the bottom of a warm, shallow tropical sea. The teeth were the only hard part of the fish's body and all that is usually fossilised, since the skeleton was made of cartilage. A pair of teeth was present in both jaws. They were used to crush the shells and crustaceans that the fish ate.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish , Rhizodus hibberti, collected from the Black Band, Calciferous Sandstone Series, Strathclyde Group of Early Carboniferous, Dinantian, Visean, Asbian (?) age from Dalkieth Coalfield, Midlothian, Scotland.
NarNarrative: This tooth is from an early bony fish that grew to a length of 6 or 7 metres. It belonged to a group of fishes with lobe-shaped fins that also included the coelacanths. Rhizodus had two large fang-like teeth (tusks) at the front of the jaw that grew up to 22cm in length. The strong, pointed teeth were ideal for hunting prey of smaller fish and amphibians in the freshwater rivers and lakes where the fish lived.
GeoRock: Strathclyde Group & Calciferous Sandstone Series & Black Band

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish (tooth), Janassa bituminosa, collected from the Marl SLate of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ1 age from Middridge, Co Durham (NE England). Collected by Joseph Duff. Group of teeth in jaw.
NarNarrative: These are the teeth of a fossil fish called Janassa bituminosa. It was a large, flat, ray-like fish. It lived in the Zechstein Sea, a tropical sea that existed 250 million years ago. Janassa lived on the seabed, and used these strong, blunt teeth to crush and eat shellfish. As the teeth in each jaw were worn away they were pushed out and replaced by new ones growing from beneath...just like in sharks today. The skin of this fish was covered in tiny bony knobs, known as denticles. Its skeleton was made of cartilage and usually only the bony knobs and teeth are preserved.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Acrolepis sp., collected from the Marl Slate of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ1 age from Middridge, Co Durham (NE England). Collected by Joseph Duff.
NarNarrative: Acrolepis was a large predatory fish that lived in the warm, Zechstein Sea 250 million years ago. This sea streched from what is now north east England to Germany and Poland. This fish was probably similar to the modern pike, living alone, and eating smaller fish like the common Palaeoniscum. Acrolepis measured about 60 centimetres in length, compared to the 10 to 18 centimetre length of Palaeoniscum.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Pygopterus mandibularis, collected from the Marl SLate of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ1 age from Cullercoats, Whitley Bay, Tyne and Wear (NE England).
NarNarrative: This is a complete fossil of the fish Pygopterus mandibularis. This was a large predatory (hunting) fish. We know that it ate smaller fish like Palaeoniscum, because we have found the fossilised remains of Palaeoniscum inside the stomach of the larger Pygopterus. This fossil is from Cullercoats, from rocks that are 250 million years old.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil mammal (Mammoth), Mammuthus primigenius, collected from unspecified rocks of Quaternary, Pleistocene age from Worms near Pfalz, Germany. Juvenile lower jaw with two milk molars.
NarNarrative: Woolly mammoths became extinct about 10 000 years ago and are symbolic of the Ice Ages in the Quaternary period. They are well known from Stone Age (Palaeolithic) cave paintings, especially in France, and the discovery of complete bodies in frozen ground in Siberia. They had long, black hair and a hump of fat behind the head, used as a food source (like camels). This lower jaw bone with two milk molars is from a juvenile (young) mammoth. The distinctive ridges on the teeth are typical of mammoths and were used to grind down the tough plants that they fed on.
ComName_tab: Mammoth, Mammuthus primigenius, Mammuthus primigenius
SciName: Mammuthus primigenius : Elephantidae : Proboscidea : Mammalia : Chordata
LocalSum: Europe, Germany, Pfalz (nr.), Worms

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish , Sparnodus macrophthalmus, collected from the 'Fish Beds' of Tertiary, Middle Eocene, Lutetian - Bartonian age from Monte Bolca, Verona, Italy. Collected by N.C. Cookson.
NarNarrative: This tropical fossil fish was collected from one of Europe's earliest and most famous fossil localities, Monte Bolca, 30 km northwest of Verona in the Italian Alps. The fossil fish found there convinced 16th century naturalists that fossils were actually the remains of living organisms. The fish are preserved in a rock deposited on a seabed where there was no oxygen. This stopped bacteria growing and causing decay. The fossils are therefore very well preserved. This fossil is named after it's large eyes (macro meaning large, and opthalmus meaning eyes).
ComName_tab: sparnodus & macrophthalmus, Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: Italy, Verona, Monte Bolca

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish (tooth), Sagenodus inaequalis, collected from the Coal Measures Group rocks rocks of Late Carboniferous, Westphalian, Langsettian - Duckmantian age from Newsham Colliery, Blyth, Northumberland (NE England). Toothplate.
NarNarrative: Sagenodus is a type of lung-fish that had an eel-like body and grew up to 30 cm in length. Lungfish were the first vertebrates (animals with backbones) adapted to breath air. They lived in shallow, salt and fresh water that was liable to become stagnant and dry up. The tooth plate formed part of a jaw palate that was used to crush the mollusc shells and crustaceans that the fish ate.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish , Lepidotus sp., collected from the Lias of Early Jurassic age.
NarNarrative: This fossil is part of the body of the Jurassic fish Lepidotus. Incomplete fossils like this one are much more common than complete fossils. When an animal dies, and starts to decay, it needs to be buried quickly in order to stay together. Palaeontologists (people who study fossils), have to look for clues, to decide what sort of animal (or plant), a fossil is from. The shiny black diamond-shaped pieces covering the surface of this fossil are fish scales. It is quite easy to identify fish scales when there are several of them like this, because they form a clear pattern.
ComName_tab: lepidotus & sp. (agassiz), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: no locality data

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish , Mesodon bucklandi, collected from the Coral Rag of Middle Jurassic, Bathonian age from Weymouth (north shore), Dorset (SW England).
NarNarrative: The smooth rounded pebble-like parts of this fossil are the teeth of the now-extinct fish Mesodon bucklandi. Rounded teeth like these ones would be used for chewing and crushing food. Their shape is very different from the sharp, pointed teeth that other types of fish use to hold and tear their food.
ComName_tab: mesodon & bucklandi, Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: UK, England, Dorset (SW England), Weymouth (north shore)

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Osteolepis macrolepidotus Agassiz, collected from unspecified rocks of Middle Devonian age from Orkney (Scotland). Collected by David M. Lumsden.
NarNarrative: Osteolepis macrolepidotus was a large fish with a powerful tail, and was probably a scavenger, feeding on whatever was available. It would have lived in a large, fresh water lake, which was probably not very rich in oxygen, especially the deeper water. These conditions were not ideal for the animals living in the lake, but would have been ideal for the preservation and fossilisation of the fish once they were dead.
ComName_tab: , Sarcopterygii & Crossoptergyii (After Romer)
LocalSum: UK, Scotland, Orkney (Scotland)

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish , Knightia alta, collected from the Green River Formation of Tertiary, Early - Middle Eocene, Ypresian - Lutetian age from Colorado, USA. Collected by David M. Lumsden.
NarNarrative: This freshwater fossil fish comes from Green River in the USA, one of the worlds 'super fossil sites'. It is the state fossil of Wyoming and was named after the first state geologist, Wilbur Clinton Knight. Knightia is a relative of the present day herring, and grew to a length of 10 to 25 cm. They lived in large shoals. The fish population died out very suddenly and large numbers were preserved as fossils in the fine-grained lake sediments.
ComName_tab: Shark, palaeoniscid, Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: North America, USA, Colorado

ColPhysicalDescription: Plaster cast of a fossil reptile (pterodactyl), Scaphognathus sp., collected from unspecified rocks of Late Jurassic age from Germany.
NarNarrative: This is a plaster cast of a pterosaur skeleton. Pterosaurs were not dinosaurs, although they were alive at the same time. They were a group of flying reptiles that had a large flap of skin between the body and one very long finger bone to form a wing. They are often called Pterodactyls (which means 'winged finger'). They did not have feathers like birds. Pterosaurs had thin bones, many of which were hollow, giving them light skeletons. They are very important animals as they give us information about how vertebrates (animals with backbones) took to the air using true powered flight (and not just gliding).
ComName_tab: Pterosaur, Reptilia
LocalSum: Europe, Germany

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Palaeoniscum freieslebeni, collected from the Marl Slate of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ1 age from Houghton-le-Spring, Co Durham (NE England). Collected by Robinson.
NarNarrative: Palaeoniscum was a small herring-like fish that probably swam in shoals (groups of fish). 250 million years ago, when this fish was alive, the sea was much warmer than it is now, because Sunderland (near where this fossil came from), was much closer to the equator than it is today. This is because continental drift (the movement of the plates that cover the surface of the earth), causes the shape and postion of the continents to slowly change.
ComName_tab: palaeoniscum & freieslebeni (de blainville), Actinopterygii & Palaeonisciformes (After Romer)
LocalSum: UK, England, Co. Durham (NE England), Houghton-le-Spring

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil tooth, unidentified, collected from the Great Oolite of Middle Jurassic, Bathonian age from Minchinhampton, Gloucestershire (SW England).
NarNarrative: This tooth has been fossilised in a piece of oolitic limestone. We don't know what kind of animal this tooth belonged to. The tooth is long and curved, and has ridges that run along its length. The smooth, shiny end is the part of the tooth that would have been attached to the jaw bone of the animal. Oolitic limestone is a rock that contains a lot of small round grains, which you may be able to see if you look closely. It is formed in the sea near the shore.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil nest (bird), Ducks nest with eggs, collected from unspecified rocks of Tertiary (?) age.
NarNarrative: This is a nest containing the eggs of a duck. It is not a true fossil as the nest and eggs have only been covered in a layer of limestone (calcium carbonate). This calcium carbonate came from water which must have been flowing or dripping onto the nest. This is probably why the duck abandoned the eggs. The process also happens at Mother Shipton's Cave in North Yorkshire. People hang teddy bears and other items at the entrance to the cave where the petrifying waters then cover them with hard calcium carbonate.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish (tooth), Ptychodus sp., collected from the Chalk Formation of Late Cretaceous, Cenomanian - Campanian age.
NarNarrative: Teeth are extremely durable and often provide the only evidence of fish in the fossil record. This flat tooth with ridges running across the crown is from the extinct shark Ptychodus that grew up to 5m long. It would have been part of a complex interlocking "pavement" known as a jaw-plate which contained over a hundred similar teeth. The shark was a predator that fed on shellfish that were crushed between the flat teeth before being swallowed.

At the time the rocks were being deposited the climate was changing and subtropical forests were giving way to open savannah type grassland where the mammals thrived. The soft body tissues and organs of the Rhinoceros would have been eaten by a variety of predators and scavengers before the bones rotted away leaving only the teeth.

The closest living relative of Homoeosaurus is the tuatara, a protected species that lives on islands off the coast of New Zealand. The tuatara is regarded as a 'living fossil', as it has hardly changed in more than 150 million years.

NarNarrative: Pterichthyodes was an armoured fish, which means that its body, except its tail, was covered with hard, bony plates. There are no fish like these ones alive today. They became extinct hundreds of millions of years ago, before the dinosaurs were alive. This fish has a pair of jointed bony spines, just behind its head, on either side of its body. It belonged to a group of fish called the Placoderms.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish (shark tooth), Carcharodon sp., collected from unspecified rocks of Tertiary (?) age from South Carolina, USA Collected by Captain Aitkenhead, 6th October 1885.
NarNarrative: Teeth are the most commonly fossilised parts of sharks, because they are harder than the other parts of the shark's body. Shark bones are quite soft, because they are made of cartilage instead of bone. When a shark dies, its teeth decay more slowly than the other, softer parts of its body. The more slowly parts of a dead animal decay, the more likely they are to be fossilised.

NarNarrative: In Malta, fossilised shark's teeth are known as St. Paul's tongues. St. Paul was shipwrecked on the island as he was travelling to Rome. Legend has it that he was bitten by an adder, which he threw into a fire. He put a curse on the snakes of Malta, turning their tongues to stone and making their venom harmless.

NarNarrative: Teeth often provide the only evidence of reptiles and other vertebrates (animals with backbones) in the fossil record because they are extremely tough and durable. The flesh of the crocodile would have been eaten by scavengers and the bones rotted away leaving only the teeth. This tooth was found in rocks deposited in fresh and brackish (slightly salty) water. Often the hard, bony plates (scutes) that cover the crocodile's back are also found as fossils.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil mammal (tooth), a Mastodon, Anancus anvernensis, collected from unspecified rocks of Quaternary (?) age.
NarNarrative: Mastodons are a group of mammals that evolved from the same ancestors as elephants and mammoths. They were widely distributed throughout the Northern Hemisphere and Africa until they became extinct about 2 million years ago. Climate changes in a glacial episode (ice age) destroyed their forest habitats and the plants they ate. Their name is derived from the shape of their teeth and means 'nipple toothed'. The tooth shape shows that Mastodons fed on the leaves and branches of trees and shrubs.
ComName_tab: Mastodon, Anancus arvernensis, Anancus arvernensis

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil mammal (tooth), a Cave Hyaena, Crocuta crocuta spelaea, collected from unspecified rocks of Quaternary, Late Pleistocene, Ipswichian age from Kirkdale Cave, Pickering (nr.), North Yorkshire (NE England). Kirkdale Cave written on specimen.
NarNarrative: Although living hyenas are found in warmer regions of the Old World, fossil remains show that they lived much further north during Quaternary times. As their name suggest they lived in caves and their teeth and bones are found in many cave deposits. The cave where this hyena was found included parts of the skeletons of other animals suggesting that they died elsewhere and the bits were carried back to the cave by the hyenas.
ComName_tab: Cave Hyaena, crocuta & crocuta & spelaea (goldfuss), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Mammalia

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil mammal (tooth), a Cave Bear, Ursus spelaeus, collected from the Beestonian Zone of Quaternary, Early to Middle Pleistocene age.
NarNarrative: The Cave Bear was about one third larger than the living Brown Bear and found all over northern Eurasia until they became extinct about 70 000 years ago. Climate changes during a glaciation (ice age) destroyed their coniferous (evergreen) forest habitat and food supply. As its name implies the bear lived in caves and so its teeth are often found in cave deposits. In summer the Cave Bear fed mainly on plant foods it found in the coniferous forests.
ComName_tab: Cave Bear, Ursus spelaeus, Ursus spelaeus

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Diplomystus brevissimus, collected from the 'Fish Beds' of Late Cretaceous, Cenomanian age from Mount Lebanon, Lebanon, Syria. Several well preserved small fish on slab of fine grained calcareous mudstone.
NarNarrative: The bony skeletons and patches of skin of these small herring-lie fish are well preserved in the fine-grained host rock. Like modern herring they lived in shoals near the surface of the sea where they fed on small animals. They grew up to 10cm long. They have been so well preserved because there was no oxygen in the water on the sea floor. This stopped their bodies decaying and also meant that other animals could not eat their bodies.
ComName_tab: Diplomystus brevissimus, Diplomystus brevissimus
LocalSum: Syria, Mount Lebanon

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Knightia alta, collected from the Green River Formation of Tertiary, Early - Middle Eocene, Ypresian - Lutetian (?) age from Green River, Wyoming, U.S.A.. Collected by David M. Lumsden. Single well preserved fish on slab of calcareous mudstone.
NarNarrative: This freshwater fossil fish comes from Green River in the USA, one of the worlds 'super fossil sites'. It is the state fossil of Wyoming and was named after the first state geologist, Wilbur Clinton Knight. Knightia is a relative of the present day herring and grew to a length of 10 to 25 centimetres. The fish population died out suddenly when oxygen levels fell dramatically. This is the reason that large numbers were preserved in the fine-grained lake sediments.
ComName_tab: Knightia alta, Knightia alta
LocalSum: North America, USA, Wyoming

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a trace fossil, unidentified reptilian footprints, collected from unspecified rocks of Triassic age.
NarNarrative: The two rows of footprints on this slab of red sandstone form a track made by an unidentified animal as it walked across sand. It had five toes on each foot. We don't know where this piece of sandstone came from, but it is probably British, and possibly from the Berwick (Northumberland) area. When the animal walked over soft sand it left an impression of its foot. This impression was then filled by another layer of sand which protected the footprint. As the sand hardened to form sandstone, the footprint became a fossil. Fossils of footprints are called 'trace-fossils' because they are not actually the remains of the animal, but rather the marks it left behind.
ComName_tab: , Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Reptilia

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Acentrophorus varians Kirkby, collected from the Concretionary Limestone of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ2 age from Fulwell Hill, Sunderland, Tyne and Wear (NE England). Collected by James Walter Kirkby.
NarNarrative: Acentrophorus varians was a small fish, about the same size as a sardine. It lived in the Zechstein sea (a warm tropical sea), 250 million years ago. Acentophorus was adapted to survive in the very salty water. It was probably a scavenger and fed from the remains of other dead fish. It had tiny sharp, pointed teeth for tearing flesh, but was one of the smallest fish in the sea at that time and was therefore probably not a predator.
ComName_tab: acentrophorus & varians (kirkby), Actinopterygii & Neopterygii & Semionotiformes & Semionotidae
LocalSum: UK, England, Tyne and Wear (NE England), Sunderland, Fulwell Hill

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish , Knightia eoceana Cope, collected from the Green River Formation (?) of Tertiary, Early - Middle Eocene, Ypresian - Lutetian (?) age from Green River, Wyoming, USA.
NarNarrative: This freshwater fossil fish comes from the Green River Formation in the USA, one of the worlds 'super fossil sites'. It is the state fossil of Wyoming, and was named after the first state geologist, Wilbur Clinton Knight. Knightia is a relative of the present day herring, and grew to a length of 10 to 25 centimetres. It lived in large shoals. The fish population died out very abruptly and large numbers were preserved in the fine-grained lake sediments.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil trace fossil, Chondrites sp., collected from the Skiddaw Group of Early Ordovician, Arenig (?) age from Randale Beck (?), Cumbria (NW England). Collected by John Jeffrey.
NarNarrative: We do not know what animals made these fossilised burrows. They would have lived within the soft mud on the seabed, tunnelling and making the burrows as they searched for food. The burrows were then filled by mud of a different colour. Eventually the mud turned into mudstone and then into slate and the burrows became fossilised.
ComName_tab: Trace Fossil (burrows), chondrites & sp., Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata
LocalSum: UK, England, Cumbria (NW England), Randale Beck (?)

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish , Dipterus valenciennesi, collected from the Middle Old Red Sandstone of Devonian age from Banniskirk Quarry, Caithness, Scotland. Collected by Rev G.C. Abbs (?).
NarNarrative: Dipterus is a primitive lungfish that was able to breathe air. It probably lived in water that didn't contain much oxygen. The body of this fish was covered with rounded scales, that show up very clearly on this fossil. Dipterus is related to modern lungfish that live in rivers in Africa, Australia and South America.
ComName_tab: dipterus & valenciennesi, Sarcopterygii & Dipnoi (After Romer)
LocalSum: UK, Scotland, Caithness (Scotland)

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Ischnacanthus gracilis, collected from the Lower Old Red Sandstone of Devonian age from Turin Hill, Forfarshire (Scotland). Collected by J. Powrie.
NarNarrative: Ischnacanthus gracilis was a fish that had a long, scaly body. This fish had two narrow dorsal spines, one either side of and just behind its head. It was a predatory (hunting) fish, and probably lived in Lake Forfar in Angus, Scotland, a fresh-water lake surrounded by volcanoes. In this specimen the fossil is the dark area, The deep grooves around it are where tools have been used to chisel away the rock.
ComName_tab: ischnacanthus & gracilis (egerton), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: UK, Scotland, Fife (Scotland), Turin Hill

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Coccosteus cuspidatus, collected from unspecified rocks of Middle Devonian age from Lethen Bar, Nairnshire (Scotland). Collected by Thomas Atthey.
NarNarrative: Coccosteus was a Devonian fish that had its head and part of its body covered with bony plates, which can easily be seen in this fossil. This fish was a hunter. The bony plates of its jaw had sharp, serrated edges (a bit like a steak knife), which helped it to tear through the flesh of its prey (the animals that it ate). The tail of Coccosteus is not covered in bony plates, so this part of the fish is less commonly fossilised. (The soft parts often decay before the animal is buried and preserved). Thomas Atthey, who collected this fossil, is better known for his collection of local Carboniferous fish in the Hancock Museum.
ComName_tab: coccosteus & cuspidatus (miller), Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: UK, Scotland, Highland (Scotland), Lethen Bar

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Asterolepis maximus, collected from unspecified rocks of Middle Devonian age from Nairn, Inverness-shire (Scotland). Collected by Mr W. Waters.
NarNarrative: Asterolepis maxima was an armoured fish that lived during the Middle to Late Devonian. The upper part of its body and its head were covered with protective bony plates. The plates were covered with a raised pattern of wart like lumps. Asterolepis probably lived on the sea floor, searching for food in layers of mud. This fossil shows the plates that covered the main body of the fish. The head, armoured fins and tail are all missing. Fish like these are very primitive and do not have many of the special adaptations that modern fish have.
ComName_tab: asterolepis & maximus, Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: UK, Scotland, Highland (Scotland), Nairn

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Asterolepis maximus, collected from unspecified rocks of Middle Devonian age from Nairn, Nairnshire (Scotland). Collected by W. Waters.
NarNarrative: Asterolepis maxima was a primitive armoured fish, which had bony plates covering its head and the upper part of its body, giving it a box like shape. Fish like this are now extinct, but were quite common during the Middle and Late Devonian. Asterolepis probably live on the sea floor, scavenging in mud for food. This specimen shows one of the armoured plates from the body of the fish. If you look closely you can see that it is covered with many tiny wart-like bumps.
ComName_tab: asterolepis & maximus, Animalia & Chordata & Vertebrata & Pisces
LocalSum: UK, Scotland, Nairnshire (Scotland), Nairn

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, a Coelacanth, Coelacanthus granulatus, collected from the Marl Slate of Late Permian, Zechstein (Durham Province), EZ1 age.
NarNarrative: Coelacanthus granulatus was a fish that probably used its well-developed limb-like fins for crawling along the seabed as well as swimming. It was thought that coelacanths became extinct about 100 million years ago until a fisherman caught a live one off the coast of South Africa in 1938! They are still being caught today and are known as living fossils. Modern Ceolacanths are much larger than their earlier relatives. Many fossils of Coelacanths have been found in the local Marl Slate rocks of Co. Durham, but they are still quite rare.
ComName_tab: Coelacanth, coelacanthus & granulatus, Sarcopterygii & Crossoptergyii (After Romer)

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish (spine), Xenacanthus sp., collected from the Modiolaris Zone, Middle Coal Measures, Low Main Seam of Late Carboniferous, Westphalian, Duckmantian age from Newsham Colliery, Blyth, Northumberland (NE England). Spine.
NarNarrative: This spine was attached to the back of the head of the small freshwater shark Xenacanthus that grew up to 70cm in length. The fish had a slim narrow body with a continuous fin along its back and looked like a modern conger-eel. It lived in freshwater swamps where it hunted smaller fish for food. The narrow body helped it swim through the closely spaced swamp plants. The spine is often all that is found of the fish.
GeoRock: Coal Measures Formation (Middle) & Low Main Seam

NarNarrative: Platysomus was a deep bodied fish that lived in the Zechstein Sea 250 million years ago. It was a slow swimmer, and may have lived among seaweed and small reefs near the shore. Platysomus had blunt cone-shaped teeth, ideal for crushing and eating shellfish. Fossils of this fish are less common than those of the herring like Palaeoniscum that lived in shoals.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil mammal, a Red Deer, Cervus elaphus, collected from unspecified rocks of Quaternary, Holocene, Flandrian age from Cresswell Bog, Middleton Hall (near Wooler), Northumberland (NE England). Collected by A. Kirkup.
NarNarrative: The bones of most land vertebrates rot away after the carcase (body) has been eaten by other scavenging animals. This Red Deer lower jaw bone with teeth has been preserved in a peat bog where the low oxygen environment stops the destructive bacteria from destroying the bone. This specimen is barely old enough to be a fossil if it is the same age as the 5 000 to 8 000 year-old peat that it was found in.

It probably lived in shoals, like herring, and was preyed upon (eaten) by larger predatory fish. Of all the fish fossils that are found in the Marl Slate, this is the most common type.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish, Diplomystus dentatus Cope, collected from the Green River Shales of Tertiary, Eocene age from Green River, Wyoming, USA.
NarNarrative: Diplomystus dentatus was a common, now extinct, herring-like fish that lived during the Eocene period, approximately 40 to 50 million years ago, in a deep fresh water lake that covered an area of approximately 25000 miles of the USA. At that time, the climate in the area was sub tropical. Diplomystus probably ate small fish that also lived in the lake, because fossils of this fish, with smaller fish in its mouth and stomach, have been found. The rock from which this fossil comes from is part of the Green River Formation.

ColPhysicalDescription: Specimen of a fossil fish (shark tooth), Lamna elegans, collected from the Red Crag of Quaternary, Early Pleistocene age from Suffolk (SE England). Collected by Edward Charlesworth (?).
NarNarrative: The elegant shape of this tooth gives the medium sized shark its second (species) name. Its first name (genus) is from Greek and means 'voracious fish'. Living relatives of the fish grow up to 3 metres long and include the mackerel-shark and porbeagle-shark that live in cool oceans and coastal waters. They are predators that feed mainly on shoals of fish such as mackerel and herring. Unusually for shark teeth the edges are not serrated (saw-toothed) for cutting up their prey.

LocalSum: UK, England, Suffolk (SE England)

ColPhysicalDescription: Part of the upper mandible of a Great Auk; mainly consisting of the premaxilla. The bone is broken off at the proximal end. This bone was discovered in April 1878 in a sea cave at Whitburn Lizards during limestone quarrying operations. A  large number of other bones and bone fragments were discovered in cave earth deposits at this site. It was identified amongst a parcel of bones sent to John Hancock in the same year.
ComName_tab: Great Auk
SciName: Pinguinus impennis : Alcidae : Charadriiformes : Aves : Chordata
LocalSum: UK, England, Tyne and Wear (NE England), South Shields, Whitburn Lizards
